      "type": "thinking",
      "text": "**Refining FitConnect Vision**\n\nI'm now fully immersed in the FitConnect project. My current focus is nailing down the core structure with React 18+, aiming to precisely match the HTML blueprint. I'm prioritizing TypeScript integration and the elegant styling capabilities of Tailwind CSS.\n\n\n**Developing Component Structure**\n\nI've been concentrating on the component breakdown, integrating Tailwind CSS styling via CDN. I'm leaning towards `lucide-react` for icons and have started envisioning the layout: Navbar, Hero, Search, Trainer Results, How It Works, Trust & Safety, Featured Trainers, and Footer.  Mock data and filter logic are also being considered.  I need to figure out where to best introduce recharts or d3 for data visualization.\n\n\n**Exploring Visualization Options**\n\nI'm now contemplating how to integrate data visualizations.  The current plan is to add a Recharts-powered \"Savings Calculator\" or a \"Market Rates vs. FitConnect Rates\" chart within a new \"Market Insights\" section. I'm keen on the idea of showcasing savings potential to users.\n\n\n**Optimizing Hero Design**\n\nI'm now focused on the Hero section, exploring a canvas-based particle effect using React's `useRef` and `useEffect` to avoid p5.js bloat. Alternatively, a CSS animation offers a reliable backup. I've also solidified my library choices, going with Recharts, lucide-react, and Framer Motion for optimal React integration and performance.\n\n\n**Initiating Coding Phase**\n\nI'm now in the thick of coding. I've defined the app structure and data models: `Trainer` interface, `Specialty` enum, and mock trainer data. I'm focusing on key components: a sticky navbar, hero section with canvas particles, reusable `TrainerCard`, search functionality with filter state, and a Market Insights section showcasing savings with `recharts`. A featured trainers carousel and overall App assembly are underway, with basic boilerplate in place. I'm leveraging `recharts` for the main visualizations, reserving `d3` for potentially more intricate data interactions.\n\n\n**Revisiting D3 Integration**\n\nI'm reconsidering the D3 implementation, aiming for practical uses. A Recharts graph for savings is still the core, but I'll add a D3 \"Activity Heatmap\" on a trainer card or a \"Fitness Trends\" section to showcase D3 integration. I'll maintain simplicity, leveraging Recharts for most visualizations and reserving D3 for specific, focused components.\n\n\n**Organizing File Structure**\n\nNow, I've outlined the project's file structure meticulously. I'm focusing on a clean, maintainable layout: essential files like `metadata.json`, `types.ts`, and `constants.ts` (mock data) will be separate. The `components/ui/Button.tsx` is being worked on and will be reusable. I've broken down major sections like the Navbar, Hero, TrainerCard, SearchSection, MarketInsights (with Recharts), HowItWorks, FeaturedTrainers, TrustSafety, and Footer.  Finally, `App.tsx`, `index.tsx`, and `index.html` are the entry points.\n\n\n**Showcasing Cost Savings**\n\nI'm now integrating a comparison to show clear cost advantages, like \"Average Gym Price: $100\" versus \"FitConnect Price: $50\".  This will reinforce the value proposition.\n\n\n",
